# Cursor Rule / Skill / Subagent Discipline

If you are editing any file under `.cursor/rules/`, `.cursor/skills/`, or
`.cursor/agents/`, the change is not done until you have ALSO performed
two bookkeeping steps:

## 1. Bump `lastUpdated:` in the file's frontmatter

Every rule/skill/subagent file has a YAML frontmatter block:

```yaml
---
description: ...
alwaysApply: ... or globs: [...]
lastUpdated: YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SSZ
---
```

When you edit the file, update `lastUpdated:` to the current ISO 8601
UTC timestamp. Use the system `date` command — never guess:

```bash
date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ
```

This format matches the precedent set by
`.cursor/figma/state/last-sync.json` `lastSuccessfulSync` and is the
canonical timestamp shape for "when did this happen" across the repo.
The trailing `Z` indicates UTC explicitly so cloud-agent and local-agent
edits sort unambiguously regardless of timezone.

If the file is a brand new rule/skill/subagent and doesn't have
frontmatter yet, add the full block. The required fields are:

| Field | Rules | Skills | Subagents |
|---|---|---|---|
| `description:` | required | required | required |
| `name:` | n/a | required | required |
| `alwaysApply:` | required | n/a | n/a |
| `globs:` | optional (when `alwaysApply: false`) | n/a | n/a |
| `model:` | n/a | n/a | optional |
| `lastUpdated:` | required | required | required |

## 2. Regenerate `.cursor/TOOLCHAIN.md`

```bash
bash scripts/regenerate-toolchain.sh
```

[`.cursor/TOOLCHAIN.md`](../TOOLCHAIN.md) is the index of every
rule/skill/subagent in the repo. **Do not hand-edit it** — the
regenerator script overwrites the tables on every run from the
frontmatter of the source files. Any manual edits to the tables will
be lost.

The script handles every bookkeeping case automatically:

- **Edited an existing file** — its row's date column updates from
  the new `lastUpdated:`; description column updates if you changed
  the frontmatter `description:`.
- **Added a new file** — a new row appears in the right section
  (Rules, Skills, or Subagents). The section count in the heading
  also updates (e.g. `## Rules (15)` → `## Rules (16)`).
- **Removed a file** — its row disappears. The section count
  decrements.
- **Renamed a file** — the link target and date update.

If you also want to re-stamp every file's `lastUpdated:` to the same
moment (rare — typically only done after a deliberate "audit
everything" pass), run:

```bash
bash scripts/seed-toolchain-timestamps.sh
```

## Why this discipline exists

Without `lastUpdated:` and `TOOLCHAIN.md` discipline:

- An agent reading a rule has no in-context way to tell whether the rule
  is fresh or months old.
- When two rules conflict, the agent has no temporal hint about which is
  newer.
- A cloud agent and a local agent can drift on the instruction layer
  without either knowing.

The same SITE_CHANGELOG and per-component `changelog.json` discipline
exists for the documentation site. This is the agent-toolchain
equivalent.

